<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900921-0053</DOCNO><DOCID>900921-0053.</DOCID><HL>   Arbitrage Activity in Week   Is Dominated by 2 Firms</HL><DATE>09/21/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16</SO><CO>   MS MER GE BSC</CO><IN>STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)STOCK INDEXES (NDX)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- Bear Stearns Cos. and Morgan Stanley GroupInc. accounted for about half of all stock-index arbitrageactivity on the New York Stock Exchange for the week endedSept. 7.   In its regular weekly report on computer-aided programtrading, the Big Board said program trading accounted for9.8% of average daily volume, or 11.4 million shares a day.That was down from 12.7% the previous week.</LP><TEXT>   Index arbitrage -- rapid-fire purchases and sales ofbaskets of stocks with offsetting trades in futures andoptions -- accounted for 53.9% of total program trading byall firms. Bear Stearns used arbitrage in nearly all itsprogram trading; Morgan Stanley used it in slightly more thanhalf.   Overall, the busiest program traders were Morgan Stanley(10 million shares), Bear Stearns (6.8 million), MerrillLynch andamp; Co. (5.7 million), General Electric Co.'s Kidder,Peabody andamp; Co. (4.3 million) and CS First Boston Inc.'s FirstBoston Corp. (4.2 million). Bear Stearns and Kidder did mostof their trading for their own accounts; the other firms forcustomers' accounts.   &quot;Buy&quot; programs accounted for an average 3.8 million sharesand &quot;sell&quot; programs for 7.6 million, during a week in whichthe Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 0.2%.   Program trading is the purchase or sale of a basket of atleast 15, and often hundreds, of stocks with a value of atleast $1 million.</TEXT></DOC>